datastore.fieldTips: This field was created by {{user}} in {{time}}

formula.funcAdd: Adds numbers to return the sum, or adds numbers and a date to return a new date. If adding numbers and a date, treats the numbers as milliseconds. Accepts any number of argument expressions, but at most, one expression can resolve to a date.
formula.funcAnd: Returns true only when all its expressions evaluate to true. Accepts any number of argument expressions.
formula.funcCond: A ternary operator that evaluates one expression, and depending on the result, returns the value of one of the other two expressions. Accepts either three expressions in an ordered list or three named parameters.
formula.funcDateToString: Returns the date as a formatted string.
formula.funcDivide: Returns the result of dividing the first number by the second. Accepts two argument expressions.
formula.funcEq: Returns true if the values are equivalent.
formula.funcGt: Returns true if the first value is greater than the second.
formula.funcGte: Returns true if the first value is greater than or equal to the second.
formula.funcIfNull: Returns either the non-null result of the first expression or the result of the second expression if the first expression results in a null result. Null result encompasses instances of undefined values or missing fields. Accepts two expressions as arguments. The result of the second expression can be null.
formula.funcLt: Returns true if the first value is less than the second.
formula.funcLte: Returns true if the first value is less than or equal to the second.
formula.funcMonth: Returns the month for a date as a number between 1 (January) and 12 (December).
formula.funcMultiply: Multiplies numbers to return the product. Accepts any number of argument expressions.
formula.funcNe: Returns true if the values are not equivalent.
formula.funcNot: Returns the boolean value that is the opposite of its argument expression. Accepts a single argument expression.
formula.funcOr: Returns true when any of its expressions evaluates to true. Accepts any number of argument expressions.
formula.funcSubtract: Returns the result of subtracting the second value from the first. If the two values are numbers, return the difference. If the two values are dates, return the difference in milliseconds. If the two values are a date and a number in milliseconds, return the resulting date. Accepts two argument expressions. If the two values are a date and a number, specify the date argument first as it is not meaningful to subtract a date from a number.
formula.funcTip1: 1. You can directly enter the formula you need to use, or you can use the formula generator to generate it.
formula.funcTip2: 2. When using a function, you need to pay attention to the brackets containing parameters, and multiple parameters need to be included with [] and separated by commas.
formula.funcTip3: 3. If you use a field as a parameter, you need to use square brackets to enclose the field. The format is as follows: x.xx, you can directly use the field selector to insert the corresponding field.
formula.funcTip4: 4. Strings need to be enclosed in double quotation marks.
formula.funcTip5: 5. After the formula input is completed, the verification must be completed manually before logging into the system.
formula.funcYear: Returns the year for a date as a number (e.g. 2014).
